\begin_layout Abstract
Many creatures ranging from geckos to beetles can easily climb on surfaces
 with the help of hairy adhesive pads on their legs.
 The hairy pad's design allows the animal to rapidly switch between strong
 adhesion during attachment and weak adhesion during detachment.
 Several studies explain this mechanism based on the asymmetric geometry
 of the hairs, which imparts direction dependent adhesion properties.
 Here, we propose a mechanism for controlling adhesion of a hairy pad based
 on a simple spring model.
 We show that the adhesion force can be decreased just by slightly tilting
 the pad during pull-off.
 Larger number of hairs are shown to decrease adhesion by a larger factor
 for a similar tilt.
 Further, deformation of the pad's soft backing layer can trigger its spontaneou
s detachment at low tilt angles due to an elastic recoil effect.
 Our model provides a new approach to switch the adhesion state in bio-inspired
 synthetic array-based adhesives without the need of asymmetric structures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over the past few decades, there has been numerous studies to understand
 how animals such as geckos and insects are able to walk on surfaces in
 any direction defying gravity.
 A microscopic observation reveals that, in many cases, animals have a dense
 array of hairy structures at the end of their legs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN198,RN59"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These hairy adhesive pads help the animal to stay attached to any surface,
 supporting its weight, and detach easily at will.
 Previous attempts to theoretically explain adhesion in hairy pads
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN40,RN120"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has followed two fundamental approaches: either by energy balance, or by
 force balance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the energy balance approach, adhesion is characterized by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

work of adhesion
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (W
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
adh
\end_layout

\end_inset

) which is the energy required to separate a pad from the surface.
 During detachment, elastic energy stored in the hair is dissipated, which
 increases W
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
adh
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and thus adhesion is enhanced
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN29,RN114"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Detachment of an individual hair can be explained based on Kendall's peeling
 theory
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN147"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which predicts low forces at high peeling angles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the force balance approach, adhesion is characterized by pull-off force,
 F
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (or stress, σ
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

), which is the maximum force necessary to separate two surfaces from contact.
 Based on a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cohesive zone model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, Hui et.
 al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN72"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 had identified two regimes of hair detachment: 1) a flaw sensitive regime,
 where contact failure occurs due to crack propagation leading to low σ
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 2) a flaw insensitive regime, where the contact interface fails simultaneously
, leading to high σ
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
p
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Tian et.
 al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN230"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 had shown that the spatula shaped hair tips in a gecko's toe allows it
 to change adhesion by three orders of magnitude by laterally sliding and
 controlling the pulling angle.
 Federle
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN20"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 had further argued that the curved shape of hairs helps the pad to stay
 attached when pulled proximally, and easily detached by elastic recoil
 when pushed distally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theories presented so far suggests that low detachment force of a hairy
 pad can be attained by 1) increasing the stress concentration by peeling
 the pad at high angles, or 2) laterally shearing the pad before pull-off,
 which requires the hairs to have an asymmetric geometry.
 However, some insects like male dock beetles predominantly have nearly
 symmetric flat 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mushroom
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 tipped hairs on their pads
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN19"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These hairs has been shown to possess superior adhesive strength
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN112"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, but the lack of asymmetry in their geometry raises the question of how
 the beetle can easily detach them during locomotion.
 Further, fabrication of synthetic mimics with asymmetric micro-pillar structure
s are generally difficult.
 It is thus desired to have alternate strategies to achieve reversible adhesion
 suited for practical applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this work, we theoretically investigate the possible mechanisms of detachment
 of hairy adhesive pads via the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spring contact model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN117"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This model is based on the force-balance approach, which assumes the hairy
 pad to behave like an array of springs.
 We hope our work to provide new strategies to control adhesion force of
 an artificial micro-pillar adhesive, with applications in bio-inspired
 robotic systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hairy pad is assumed to be a one dimensional array of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 hairs, each behaving like a spring with spring constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{h}$
\end_inset

, and natural length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,0}$
\end_inset

 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The array is attached to a linearly deformable leg, assumed to be another
 spring with spring constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{l}$
\end_inset

, and natural length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{l,0}$
\end_inset

.
 The leg is hinged to the array at a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, from the tip along the array.
 The hinge is at a vertical distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{s}$
\end_inset

, from the surface.
 The hairs are spaced apart by a width, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, and the array is of length, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 The pad is oriented at an angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, while making contact with a flat smooth surface.
 Each hair can attain a maximum length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

, before pull-off, such that its pull-off force, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{p}=k_{h}\left(l_{h,p}-l_{h,0}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{net}$
\end_inset

 is the net force on the pad and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{net}$
\end_inset

 is the the net torque about the hinge, at a particular instant during the
 detachment process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure1-model_schematic.svg
	lyxscale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Spring contact model of a hairy adhesive pad with a soft backing layer.
 The pad is oriented at a tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, with the surface.
 The pad has a total number of hairs, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

, of which, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 number of hairs are in contact with the surface at a particular instant.
 The left most hair in contact is at its maximum length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

, just before it detaches.
 The arrow along the surface indicates positive axis direction, and its
 corresponding origin is labelled as thus.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Schematic"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Change 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

hairs
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

array
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, check everywhere in text.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose at a particular instant, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs in contact with the surface.
 For a particular tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, the net force on the whole pad at a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{s}$
\end_inset

, from the surface is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{net}\left(d_{s},n,\theta\right)=\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}-l_{h,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simplifying, we get (see Appendix section for derivation):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{net}\left(d_{s},n,\theta\right)=nk_{h}\left[d_{s}-l_{h,0}-\left(s-\frac{n-1}{2}w\right)\sin\theta\right]\label{eq:force_n_d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a particular value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is valid until a certain distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{s,max}$
\end_inset

, above which its left most hair will detach.
 Just before detachment, this hair will be at its maximum length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

.
 From simple geometry we can thus find:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{s,max}\left(n,\theta\right)=l_{h,0}+\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}}+\left[s-\left(n-1\right)w\right]\sin\theta\label{eq:d_max}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 will be valid for 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{s}\leq d_{s,max}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The maximum possible adhesion of the array would be the case when all hairs
 detach simultaneously:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{max}=N_{t}f_{p}\label{eq:simul_detach}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The net torque, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{net}$
\end_inset

, about the hinge can be similarly found (see Appendix) to be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{net}\left(d_{s},n,\theta\right)=nk_{h}\cos\theta\left[\left(d_{s}-l_{h,0}\right)\left(s-\frac{n-1}{2}w\right)-\left\{ \left(s-\frac{n-1}{2}w\right)^{2}+\frac{n^{2}-1}{12}w^{2}\right\} \sin\theta\right]\label{eq:moment_n_d}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us look at the scenario where even the leg behind the array deforms
 together with the hairs.
 When a hair detaches from the surface, the leg undergoes an elastic recoil
 due to the stored elastic energy.
 Suppose the leg relaxes upward by a length 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs in contact, the force balance before and after a hair detaches is
 given respectively by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}-l_{h,0}\right)=k_{l}\left(l_{l}-l_{l,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\stackrel[i=1]{n-1}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}+\Delta l-l_{h,0}\right)=k_{l}\left(l_{l}-\Delta l-l_{l,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving the above two equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta l=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}\left(n-1\right)+k_{l}}\label{eq:backing_deform}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{s}$
\end_inset

 increases by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 in equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:moment_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 at each event of hair detachment (i.e.
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{s}=d_{s,max}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The forces and distance are expressed in non-dimensional forms, as below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{f}_{p}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w},\quad\hat{F}_{net}=\frac{F_{net}}{k_{h}w},\quad\hat{d_{s}}=\frac{d_{s}-l_{h,0}}{w},\quad\hat{s}=\frac{s}{w}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 is a parameter which encapsulates the hair's adhesion force, stiffness
 and geometry.
 Unless specified, positive force values represent attraction by convention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Detachment mechanisms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider three possible mechanisms to detach the hairy adhesive pad from
 a surface: 1) 
\emph on
Fixed pull
\emph default
, where the pad is pulled vertically up while keeping a fixed hinge, 2)
 
\emph on
Free pull,
\emph default
 where the pad is pulled vertically up while keeping the hinge free to allow
 rotation of the array and 3) 
\emph on
Flex
\emph default
, where the pad is hinged to an external point and detached in a rotary
 fashion.
 To analyse each case in detail, let us assume a pad with 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}=25$
\end_inset

 hairs and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}=0.1$
\end_inset

 attached to a stiff leg (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{l}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

).
 The situation of a soft leg (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{l}/k_{h}=10$
\end_inset

) is also considered for the first two cases involving vertical detachment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fixed pull
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Case1-Fixed_pull.svg

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Force distance curves for a hairy pad, pulled vertically upwards with a
 fixed hinge between the pad and the leg (
\emph on
Fixed pull
\emph default
).
 The leg is either stiff (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{l}\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

) or soft (
\begin_inset Formula $k_{l}/k_{h}=10$
\end_inset

).
 Positive force values represent attraction.
 The green dashed line represents the maximum possible adhesion for the
 pad, which occurs at no tilt.
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Fixed-pull"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hairy adhesive pad can be detached by pulling it vertically upwards
 while maintaining a constant tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, with the surface.
 This can be achieved if the hinge connecting the leg to the array is kept
 fixed.
 Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:d_max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:simul_detach"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can be used to get the resulting force-distance curves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increasing the tilt of the pad decreases its maximum force or adhesion (Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Fixed-pull"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Tilting the pad causes an inhomogeneous deformation of hairs, where, on
 one end they are stretched, while, on the other end they are compressed.
 The balance of the respective attractive and repulsive elastic forces of
 the hairs ultimately results in a decrease in the net force.
 We term this effect as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
elastic crippling
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In comparison, when there is no tilt, all the hairs undergo identical deformati
on and ultimately detaches simultaneously after a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d_{s}}=0.1$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, no 
\emph on
elastic crippling
\emph default
 occurs and the pad shows the maximum possible adhesion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case of a stiff leg, we see that at small distances, all hairs of
 the pad are in contact and under compression, resulting in a linear force
 response.
 On further pulling, the hairs will start to detach sequentially from left
 to right, indicated by a characteristic 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

saw-tooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fluctuations in the force curves.
 The hairs of the pad with a higher tilt angle will start to detach first,
 followed by the ones with a lower tilt.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the case of a soft leg, we observe a similar effect of tilt angle on
 the force curves as before.
 The maximum adhesion force at a particular tilt is the same as that for
 the stiff leg.
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

saw-tooth
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 fluctuations are however minimized due to the leg's deformation, leading
 to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dampened
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 force response.
 Interestingly, the force abruptly drops to zero for the angles 
\begin_inset Formula $0.2\textdegree$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.4\textdegree$
\end_inset

.
 This is an effect of the elastic recoil of the leg while each hair loses
 contact during the detachment process (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backing_deform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The length difference between the detached hair just before it breaks contact
 and its adjacent hair is 
\begin_inset Formula $w\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 If the recoil length, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l>w\sin\theta$
\end_inset

, the adjacent hair will be stretched more than its maximum length (
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

), and thus will also detach, leading to further recoil of the leg.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backing_deform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 increases with each loss of hair contact when 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is constant.
 This implies that, once initiated, the leg's recoil will always be large
 enough to detach every subsequent hair, resulting in a spontaneous propagation
 of the detachment front until the pad completely breaks contact with the
 surface.
\end_layout

