\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Presence of a soft backing layer can trigger a spontaneous detachment of
 hairs, which propagates by elastic recoil as the they are detached sequentially.
 Such a mode of detachment is triggered when the tilt angle is less than
 a critical value, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prop_thetac"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 A softer backing layer (i.e.
 low 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{b}/k_{h}$
\end_inset

) or a large value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 shifts 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

 to higher values, thus increasing the available range of tilt angles to
 trigger spontaneous detachment (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Critical-tilt-angle"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This can be explained from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backing_deform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where a high 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f_{p}}$
\end_inset

 or low 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{b}/k_{h}$
\end_inset

 will increase the backing layer's elastic recoil when a hair breaks contact,
 thus increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 However, a larger value of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 will decrease 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

, making it less feasible to trigger spontaneous detachment.
