\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>0\textdegree$
\end_inset

, the hairs will detach sequentially from left to right.
 Suppose at a particular instant (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Schematic"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), there are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs in contact with the surface.
 The origin is assumed to lie at the midpoint along the surface where the
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs are making contact.
 The pad is at a vertical distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

, from the origin.
 For a particular tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, the net force on the whole pad at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 from the surface is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{net}\left(d,n,\theta\right)=\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}-l_{h,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,i}$
\end_inset

 is the length of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 hair, which is at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from the origin.
 From simple geometry, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,i}=d'-x\tan\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Substituting in above and noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}x=0$
\end_inset

 by symmetry, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{net}\left(d,n,\theta\right)=nk_{h}\left(d'-l_{h,0}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From geometry, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 is related as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{\tan\theta}-\frac{d'}{\tan\theta}=\frac{\left(N_{t}-1\right)w\cos\theta}{2}-\frac{\left(n-1\right)w\cos\theta}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eliminating 
\begin_inset Formula $d'$
\end_inset

 from the above two equations, we find the net force on the pad as a function
 of distance to be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{net}\left(d,n,\theta\right)=nk_{h}\left(d-l_{h,0}-\frac{N_{t}-n}{2}w\sin\theta\right)\label{eq:force_n_d-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a particular value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is valid until a certain distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{max}$
\end_inset

, above which its left most hair will detach.
 Just before detachment, this hair will be at its maximum length, 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

.
 Once again from geometry, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{max}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

 is related as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{l_{h,p}}{\tan\theta}-\frac{d_{max}}{\tan\theta}=\left(n-1\right)w\cos\theta-\frac{\left(N_{t}-1\right)w\cos\theta}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}}+l_{h,0}$
\end_inset

 in above and simplifying, we get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{max}\left(n,\theta\right)=l_{h,0}+\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}}+\left(\frac{N_{t}+1}{2}-n\right)w\sin\theta\label{eq:d_max-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is valid for 
\begin_inset Formula $d\leq d_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 We can substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{max}$
\end_inset

 in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to get the force at which the left most hair detaches from the surface:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{net}\left(n,\theta\right)=nf_{p}-\frac{n\left(n-1\right)}{2}k_{h}w\sin\theta & \qquad & d=d_{max}\label{eq:seq_detach-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_detach-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is the maximum force necessary to detach one hair of the pad when there
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 hairs in contact.
 During this sequential detachment of hairs, there exists a maximum in force
 at a particular number of contacts, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 Differentiating equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_detach-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and equating it to zero we find:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{max}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}+\frac{1}{2}\label{eq:n_max-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the above in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_detach-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the maximum adhesion force of a pad during a sequential detachment of
 its 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 hairs will be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
F_{adh}\left(\theta\right) & = & \left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
\frac{f_{p}}{2}\left[\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}+1\right]+\frac{k_{h}w\sin\theta}{8} & \qquad & N_{t}\geq N_{max}\\
N_{t}f_{p}-\frac{N_{t}\left(N_{t}-1\right)}{2}k_{h}w\sin\theta & \qquad & N_{t}<N_{max}
\end{array}\right.\label{eq:seq_adh-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{net}\left(d_{s},n,\theta\right)=\stackrel[i=1]{n}{\sum}s_{i}\left[k_{h}\left(l_{h,i}-l_{h,0}\right)\cos\theta\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The length difference between the detached hair just before it breaks contact
 and its adjacent hair is 
\begin_inset Formula $w\sin\theta$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l>w\sin\theta$
\end_inset

, the adjacent hair will be stretched more than its maximum length (
\begin_inset Formula $l_{h,p}$
\end_inset

), and thus will also detach.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backing_deform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 increases with every loss of hair contact due to decreasing value of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that, hair detachment will propagate and the pad completely
 breaks contact with the surface.
 The critical number of hairs in contact, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}$
\end_inset

, below which detachment propagates for a given tilt angle can be calculated
 by substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 from equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backing_deform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into the above inequality condition, to get:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
N_{c}=\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w\sin\theta}-\frac{k_{b}}{k_{h}}+1\label{eq:prop_nc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the above in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:d_max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we can find the critical distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{c}$
\end_inset

, above which detachment propagates:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d_{c}=\left(\frac{k_{b}}{k_{h}}+\frac{N_{t}-1}{2}\right)\sin\theta\label{eq:d_c}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prop_nc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 can also be rearranged to give us the critical tilt angle, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

, below which detachment propagates for a given pad with 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 hairs:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta_{c}=\arcsin\left[\frac{f_{p}}{k_{h}w}\left(\frac{1}{\frac{k_{b}}{k_{h}}+N_{t}-1}\right)\right]\label{eq:prop_thetac}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hairs will propagate when 
\begin_inset Formula $n<N_{c}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $d>d_{c}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta<\theta_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we assume the hairs to be softer than the backing layer (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{b}/k_{h}>1$
\end_inset

), then from equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:n_max"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:prop_nc"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{c}<N_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 Spontaneous detachment of the pad occurs only after it has reached maximum
 adhesion force by sequential detachment of hairs.
 So in this case, for a given pad with 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 hairs, the adhesion force will be given by the same equation as for sequential
 detachment (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:seq_adh"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The adhesion remains unaffected by the backing layer deformation.
 It only affects the dynamics of detachment.
 The hairs lose contact spontaneously when 
\begin_inset Formula $n<N_{c}$
\end_inset

, independent of the speed at which the pad is retracted.
 One the other hand, the net force as a function of distance will be given
 by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:force_n_d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $d\leq d_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 The distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, will however be shifted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta l$
\end_inset

 each time a hair detaches from the surface, due to the backing layer's
 deformation.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $d>d_{max}$
\end_inset

, all hairs will detach spontaneously and the force will drop to zero.
\end_layout

